    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-11-04T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-11-04T20:00:00-05:00" n="512"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d512">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.BB/11–446: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Senator <persName type="from">Austin</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-11-04T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 4, 1946—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:02 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>757. Chinese Ambassador Wellington Koo<note n="49" xml:id="d512fn49">V. K.
                        Wellington Koo, Chinese Delegate to the General Assembly.</note> in
                    conversation with me today said he had interpreted my remarks October 30 with
                    regard to armed forces as indicating US assent to giving information on forces
                    and bases in all countries outside national boundaries.<note n="50"
                        xml:id="d512fn50">In regard to Mr. Austin’s address to the General Assembly
                        on October 30, see footnote 26, <ref target="#pg_975">p. 975</ref>.</note> I
                    told Mr. Koo that my remarks extended to information concerning armed forces at
                    home as well as abroad.</p>
                <p>The Ambassador said he wished to be frank in stating that this might be very
                    embarrassing to his government. Referring to relations of Chinese Government
                    with Communists in China he said his Government would scarcely wish to reveal to
                    the Communists the size and disposition of government forces, bases, and
                    airfields in China.<note n="51" xml:id="d512fn51">For documentation on United
                        States policy with respect to the situation in China, see <ref
                            target="frus1946v09">volumes <hi rend="smallcaps">ix</hi>
                        </ref> and <ref target="frus1946v10">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">x</hi>
                        </ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I thanked Mr. Koo for bringing this aspect of the matter to my attention and
                    assured him that my Government would wish to weigh it carefully in developing
                    its position with regard to the armed forces item.</p>
                <p>Foregoing has been communicated to Cohen for the Secretary with special reference
                    to <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 253 of October 29.<note n="52"
                        xml:id="d512fn52">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_971">p. 971</ref>.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
